00:01:22.030 --> 00:01:27.800
Today's program is titled
1871, The Ruins of Paris.

00:01:27.800 --> 00:01:29.840
It features Dr. Peter Brooks,

00:01:29.840 --> 00:01:34.140 position:56%
currently a Distinguished Visiting
Scholar at The John W. Kluge Center.

00:01:34.140 --> 00:01:37.390
While at The Library of Congress
Dr. Brooks has conducted research

00:01:37.390 --> 00:01:41.110
on Gustave Flaubert, his
novel Sentimental Education

00:01:41.110 --> 00:01:46.240
and the tumultuous events
in Paris in 1870 and 1871.

00:01:46.240 --> 00:01:49.830
1871 has been called
the terrible year,

00:01:49.830 --> 00:01:53.750
as Napoleon's Third Army was
defeated in the Franco Prussian War

00:01:53.750 --> 00:01:57.400
and an insurgency called
the Paris Commune followed.

00:01:57.400 --> 00:02:00.880
It was crushed partially by the
National Government and much

00:02:00.880 --> 00:02:03.640
of central Paris was
burned as a result.

00:02:03.640 --> 00:02:08.930
Flaubert visited these ruins of
Paris and found in them a lesson,

00:02:08.930 --> 00:02:12.140
if only they had understood the
novel he had published some months

00:02:12.140 --> 00:02:17.290
earlier the cataclysmic destruction
never could have happened.

00:02:17.290 --> 00:02:21.580
Dr. Brooks will speak about
this today during his talk.

00:02:21.580 --> 00:02:23.900
Dr. Brooks is Sterling [Assumed
Spelling] Professor Emeritus

00:02:23.900 --> 00:02:26.790
